      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":10,\"target_duration_minutes\":65,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":371,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":371,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":390,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start very relaxed, first 5 minutes just finding your rhythm — legs should feel unhurried.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":55,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":371,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into your comfortable aerobic zone. Conversational effort throughout — you should be able to speak in full sentences without gasping.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":390,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease off the pace in the final 5 minutes, letting your heart rate drift back down naturally.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Begin at a very gentle jog. No need to stretch beforehand — just keep the first few minutes deliberately slow.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 2–3 minutes after finishing, then do light dynamic stretching focusing on calves and Achilles — given your history with left Achilles tendinitis, a gentle heel-drop stretch on a flat surface is a good habit here.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This Monday run is the foundation of your aerobic week. At a pace-zone index of 46.7, your easy zone (5:24–6:11/km) is where the majority of your training should live during a maintenance block — roughly 80% of weekly volume. Keeping this genuinely easy protects your Achilles tendon, supports mitochondrial density, and leaves you fresh for quality work later in the week. Resist the urge to push; the physiological benefit here comes from duration, not intensity.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"title\":\"Cruise Interval Tempo\",\"target_distance_km\":12,\"target_duration_minutes\":70,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":371,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":269,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":371,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy conversational running for 15 minutes. Let your body fully warm before any quality effort — this is especially important for Achilles health.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":269,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First cruise interval at threshold pace (4:29/km). This should feel comfortably hard — you can speak a short phrase but not a full sentence. Hold the effort steady; don't surge.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":371,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jog recovery between intervals. Keep moving — don't walk.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":269,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Second cruise interval. Aim for the same effort and pace as the first — consistency between reps is the goal, not acceleration.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":371,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jog recovery.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":269,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Third and final cruise interval. If you feel strong, hold form and rhythm — this is not the time to race it. If it feels harder than the first two, that's normal and fine.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":390,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Gradually wind down over 15 minutes. Your breathing should return to fully conversational before you stop.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"15 minutes easy running before any threshold effort. Include a few gentle strides (4 x 20 seconds at slightly quicker than easy pace) in the final 3 minutes of warmup to prime your neuromuscular system without fatiguing you.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"15 minutes very easy jog, then at least 5 minutes of walking. Follow with calf stretches and Achilles mobility work — heel raises on a flat surface, 2 x 15 reps each side.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Cruise intervals at threshold pace (4:29/km) are one of the most effective tools for maintaining lactate threshold fitness without the training stress of a full tempo run. Three 8-minute reps with short jogging recovery keeps total threshold stimulus high while managing fatigue accumulation — ideal for a maintenance phase. The physiological goal is to stress the lactate clearance system enough to retain the adaptations you've built, not to push new ceilings. Keep each rep honest and controlled.\",\"perceived_effort\":7},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Recovery Easy Run\",\"target_distance_km\":8,\"target_duration_minutes\":55,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":390,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":390,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":55,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":390,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"This is a true recovery run — stay at the slower end of your easy zone (6:11/km or even slower if you feel flat after yesterday's tempo). There is zero benefit to pushing this one. Your legs know what they need today.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Step outside and just start moving at whatever pace feels natural. If the first kilometre feels sluggish, that's fine — that's the point.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for 3–5 minutes. Consider a short foam roll on calves and left Achilles area if it feels tight after the tempo work yesterday.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Wednesday recovery runs serve a specific physiological purpose: they increase weekly volume and stimulate blood flow to repair Tuesday's threshold work, without adding meaningful additional stress. Research on recovery run pace consistently shows that the slower end of the easy range (closer to 6:11/km) is optimal here. Going faster than that delays recovery without adding fitness. Think of this run as active restoration — you're clearing the metabolic byproducts of yesterday's effort and priming Tuesday's adaptations to stick.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Interval\",\"title\":\"VO2max Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":13,\"target_duration_minutes\":75,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":371,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":248,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":371,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"20 minutes easy running. In the final 3–4 minutes, include 3 x 20-second strides at interval pace to prime your neuromuscular system before the main set.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":4,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":248,\"intensity\":\"VO2Max\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"5 x 4-minute intervals at 4:08/km (interval pace). Each rep should feel hard but controlled — a 9 out of 10 effort. You should be able to finish each rep knowing you could have held it for one more minute, but choosing not to. Focus on smooth, relaxed form even when it gets tough.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":390,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":4,\"notes\":\"3-minute easy jog recovery between each work interval. Keep moving — walking is fine if needed, but gentle jogging is preferred to keep blood flowing and clear lactate more efficiently.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":390,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"15-minute easy jog cooldown. This is important — don't skip it. Your cardiovascular system needs gradual deceleration after VO2max efforts.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"A full 20-minute warmup is non-negotiable before interval work. Your Achilles history makes a thorough warmup especially important — cold connective tissue is vulnerable tissue. Start walking, then easy jog, building gradually.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"15 minutes easy jog, then 5 minutes walking. Follow with thorough calf and Achilles stretching — seated towel pulls and standing wall stretches. Consider a brief ice application to the left Achilles area if it feels warm or tight after the session.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"VO2max intervals at 4:08/km target your maximal aerobic capacity — the upper ceiling of your aerobic engine. In a maintenance block, including one VO2max session per week is the most efficient way to retain the cardiovascular adaptations you've built. Five 4-minute reps is a moderate, manageable dose — enough stimulus to maintain VO2max fitness, not so much that recovery is compromised. The 3-minute recovery ratio allows partial but not complete recovery, which is exactly the physiological stressor we want. Monitor your left Achilles closely during and after this session — interval pace increases tendon load, so any unusual tightness or pain should be flagged before continuing.\",\"perceived_effort\":8},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run with Strides\",\"target_distance_km\":10,\"target_duration_minutes\":65,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":371,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":231,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":390,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Very easy first 5 minutes — this follows a hard Thursday session, so start gently.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":371,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Comfortable easy pace for the main body of the run. Should feel aerobic and unhurried — this is not recovery pace but also not working hard.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":231,\"intensity\":\"Repetition\",\"repetitions\":6,\"notes\":\"6 x 20-second strides at roughly repetition effort (very fast but not all-out — around 3:51/km feel). Walk or very easy jog 60 seconds between each stride. These sharpen neuromuscular speed and keep your fast-twitch fibres engaged without meaningful fatigue.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":7,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":390,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jog home to close out the run.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start easy and build gradually over the first kilometre. No formal warmup needed beyond the initial easy pace — the strides are at the end of the run when you're fully warm.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 2–3 minutes after finishing. Light stretching — focus on hip flexors, calves, and Achilles. Given the strides today, your Achilles may feel slightly loaded — that's normal, but any sharp or lingering pain should be noted.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Friday's run plays a dual role: it adds comfortable aerobic volume heading into the weekend while including short strides to maintain neuromuscular speed and running economy. Strides at the end of an easy run are a low-risk, high-reward tool — they recruit fast-twitch motor units, improve stride mechanics, and keep the legs feeling sharp without accumulating fatigue. They're placed at the end (not the beginning) so the Achilles and surrounding connective tissue are fully warm. Think of these as 'reminders' to your legs of what fast running feels like.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"CrossTrain\",\"title\":\"Cross-Training or Rest\",\"target_distance_km\":0,\"target_duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":0,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":0,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":0,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Light cross-training such as easy cycling, swimming, yoga, or strength work (bodyweight or light load). Keep intensity genuinely low — this is active recovery heading into Sunday's long run. Alternatively, take a full rest day if your body is asking for it.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"If cycling or swimming, spend the first 5 minutes warming up at a very easy effort.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"5 minutes gentle movement to finish. If doing strength work, include calf raises (eccentric heel drops especially) which have strong evidence for Achilles resilience.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Saturday is intentionally low-stress. With a long run the following day, the most important thing Saturday can do for you is not compromise Sunday. Light cross-training maintains the habit of daily movement, provides gentle circulation to support recovery, and offers an option for the days when rest feels psychologically harder than moving. Eccentric heel drops (if doing strength) are particularly worth including given your Achilles history — they're one of the most evidence-supported interventions for Achilles tendon health and resilience.\",\"perceived_effort\":2},{\"day_of_week\":0,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Long Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":20,\"target_duration_minutes\":120,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":378,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":378,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":390,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First 10 minutes at the slower end of easy — let your body wake up gradually. Sunday mornings can feel stiff; that's normal and it will pass.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":95,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":378,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into a comfortable easy pace in the range of 5:24–6:11/km. Aim for the middle of that range (around 6:18 is fine if it feels right). This should feel genuinely easy for the first hour — if it doesn't, slow down. The physiological benefit of the long run comes from duration, not pace.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":390,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Final 10 minutes gradually slowing. Arrive home feeling like you had a little left — that's the ideal long run feeling.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Don't rush out the door on Sunday. 5 minutes of gentle walking, then easy jogging. If it's cool, spend a few extra minutes warming the Achilles with slow movement before picking up pace.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk at least 5 minutes after finishing. Hydrate and refuel within 30 minutes of completing the run. Gentle stretching of calves, hamstrings, and hip flexors. A light self-massage or foam roll of the calves is worthwhile — especially around the left Achilles insertion point.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"The long run is the cornerstone of your aerobic week. At 20 km, you're maintaining the endurance base that underpins everything else in your fitness profile. For a maintenance block, keeping the long run at or near your current peak (20 km, capped at 120 minutes per your preferences) is the right call — it preserves mitochondrial density, fat oxidation efficiency, and the musculoskeletal resilience that comes from time on feet. The key discipline here is pace: this run should stay in your easy zone throughout. Your pace-zone index of 46.7 reflects a runner who has earned genuine aerobic depth, and the long run is where that gets maintained. Running too fast here is the single most common mistake experienced runners make in maintenance phases — it turns an aerobic stimulus into a recovery debt.\",\"perceived_effort\":5}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
